    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-15T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-15T20:00:00-05:00" n="410"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d410">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">721.23/2140: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gibson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-15T22:00:00-03:00"
                            >March 15, 1934—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 11:57 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>44. Department’s 24, March 13, 3 p.m. Nabuco, Secretary General of the Foreign
                    Office expresses some hope of settlement before the expiration of League mandate
                    but is less optimistic than Mello Franco. He said that there was a move for an
                    extension of mandate for 6 months but doubted whether Colombia would accept.</p>
                <p>Believing that hostilities will inevitably begin promptly on expiration of truce
                    he told me in strictest confidence that Brazil is sending troops to the frontier
                    to protect her neutrality. He says this has been told to nobody else and
                    requests that it be kept secret.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gibson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
